The wait was ridiculously long. Everything is overpriced. The food was not good. The chicken strips were gross and the ranch is even worse. The bread that came with our meals is a plain piece of toast. They could at least slap some garlic butter or something like they have done at other dairy queens. I worked at Dairy Queen over 20 years ago and the food was delicious. I would not recommend the food at this location. The ice cream was fine, but I don't think you could mess that up. I will only be back when I am craving a blizzard.< /review>

<rate>2</rate>< text>
Went here two weeks ago after skiing for ice cream with my kids. Drive thru was the only option and it took 30 minutes.

Decided against my better judgement to give it another try last night, hoping that things would be different. It was actually slower and longer - 45 minutes in the drive thru!

There's no excuse for this - obviously they are very understaffed. In n out gets twice the amount of cars through their drive thru's in half the time or less. Need to figure out how to run a faster operation - this is a FAST FOOD joint after all.

Two stars purely for the great ice cream - hard to find fault there - nothing beats a blizzard, in my opinion. But I will go to other DQ's in the future, never coming to this one again.<//text>

<Rating>3< /Rating>< Review>
This seems to be a brand new business. I was happy to see a drive-thru DQ. Not a long wait but when I did put my order in, it took them a very long time to process my card and I was starting to get nervous. Once my card was given back to me they flipped my blizzard and it started leaking from the lid they put on it. I took it they did not give me any napkins. As I was about ready to leave they told me that they had accidentally charged the car behind me and now needed to give me credit on my card. That was very upsetting. I could tell that the girl at the window was new and she was probably being trained but I ended up getting the raw end of the deal. when they gave me the ice cream I noticed they have put a lid on the small Blizzard and it was squished down so much that you could not possibly open the lid they put the spoon inside the cup through the lid and so I couldn't take the lid off and my car without making a mess and I couldn't take the spoon off either.I was going to go through the drive-thru and give it back but instead I had to figure out a way to tear off some of the lid and ended up spooning it out little by little. I was a bit disappointed to say the least. I have a dairy allergy and this was going to be a treat that I should not have picked up and then to top it off have all this happen. Encouragement not to come in and save myself from the hassle. I asked for a turtle pecan blizzard and all it had was pecans but normally they put in some sort of chocolate syrup that hardens and it didn't have it. Boohoo boohoo.<//Review>

<rating>4< /rating>< text>
Very good, but it is a bit overpriced. I've been a couple of times now and I've had good experiences, but this last time my sister's carbonara pizza was a bit too greasy and salty. Plus, the white wines they recommended seemed way too light to hold up to the strong flavors of the pizza, so I'm not sure how good their pairing suggestions really are. They did have a pretty good beer selection, though, and you can't go wrong with beer and pizza! I had the seafood pizza, which I thought was perfection. Clams, octopus, mussels, shrimp and scallops in a zesty sauce on that chewy wood-fired crust, yum. Even though it was a chilly night the warmers kept us nice and toasty on the patio. It's a little too spendy for me to visit regularly, but for a special occasion it fits the bill.</text>

<Pictures>None< /Pictures><user_name>Russell Saisho< /user_name><Rate>2<//Rate><time>1425226973730</time><userid>110704716013971109471</userid><Review>Pretentious environment and sub-par food. Reviews for Michael's were excellent and pictures of food and the space seemed promising.

We ordered a pizza with prosciutto, mushrooms, olives, mozzarella, a couple other things I'm forgetting, with a tomato based sauce and an arancini appetizer. The food came out quick. A little too quick, but a thin crust pizza and a handful of fried rice balls shouldn't take long, really. The pizza was fine. Traditional thin crust, cooked in an open fire stone oven, made with fresh quality ingredients. Unfortunately, it was slightly burnt in some spots on the underside and very soggy towards the middle. Flavor was good, but just not executed perfectly. I was even more disappointed in the arancini. They were not freshly fried, it seemed as if they were fried at some point and re-heated in the oven....a travesty. They were VERY crumbly and would not hold their form and the flavor was un-inspriring.

Our waitress was great. Very friendly and attentive. The hostesses were....interesting. I don't see myself going back to Michael's, nor suggesting it to anyone else, unless they're going for brunch to load up on cheap mimosas, maybe that'd make the experience more bearable.<//Review></record></dataset><record>

<Review>Unfortunately, I cannot recommend Camp Bow Wow Temecula. During a recent overnight boarding, when my dog came home she was unable to walk properly due to her legs collapsing under her and poor coordination. She was taken to the local pet emergency department for evaluation which resulted in a 36 hour admission and neurologist follow up who diagnosed her with a Spinal Cord Contusion.

There is no definitive proof that my dog sustained the spinal cord contusion during her stay at Camp Bow Wow Temecula so this bad review is not based on that. I understand that accidents happen and that the dogs participate in group play during their stay. The reason for this bad review is because of the staffs behavior surrounding this incident.

When my dog was sent home, her report card said that there were no incidents during her stay and that she was a "happy camper." However, when I called to inquire if they could check her record for any incidents, the woman that I spoke to said that she did not need to check the record because she remembered my dog and that all she did was bark in her kennel while she was there. This is something that should have been on the report card. I also asked if there was a way to check if my dog was accidentally dropped, jumped on by another dog, given another dogs medication, or accidentally ingested something as all of those things could cause neurologic problems. The woman became defensive and denied these things. I then asked to speak to a manager, was told that one was not there at that time, and I said I would check back when there was one.

Later on I was contacted by the owner Lisa. At that time she was very apologetic and expressed compassion about my dogs condition. She then promised me that she or another staff member would check the video footage to help identify a potential cause for her condition and follow up with me. It is now 48 hours later and I have yet to hear back from anyone at Camp Bow Wow to check on her or report that they did/did not see anything on the video footage.

This bad review is because I do not feel that my pet was safe at Camp Bow Wow- not because of her potentially getting hurt while she is there, accidents happen- but because I do not trust the staff to act and follow through in the event of an emergency. During my telephone conversation with the manager, she reported to me that after speaking to one of the staff members, one of them did see my dog "walk funny" at one point but did not act on it because she didn't know if it was normal. They never called me asking if it was normal and if I wanted her to be seen by a veterinarian. Additionally, there was no report of this observation (or about her barking lots while in her kennel) on the report card. Needless to say, I will not be taking my dog back to Camp Bow Wow and I hope this review allows you to make an informed decision about where your dog stays while you're away.

UPDATE on 4/25/19 in response to reply:
My dog does not have a history of seizures and is not prescribed seizure medication. Also, my dog did not recently have a change in her food.

I am unsure of where this narrative about her "only getting the food she was provided" and that she "had couple of seizures" and to "watch for that" came from because Ava has no neurological medical history.

I spoke with the owner 8 days ago and have not received any follow up contact via phone from the facility about our original conversation which was promised. Their review reply was posted 6 days after my original review and contains information that ought to have been communicated to me either during my dogs boarding, when she went home, or during the phone conversation with the owner afterwards. Honestly, I didn't think I could become more disappointed in their approach to handling the situation but I am .

@Camp Bow Wow Temecula: Honestly, all I wanted was solid communication to discuss what happened. Not to point fingers but to ensure that Ava gets the help that she needs. You have dropped the ball on this one.< /Review>< Pictures>

<Text>Love, love, love, CBW Temecula!  My dog Nikko is a pro and has no issues about being around other dogs.  Tucker on the other hand, hasn't had much socialization which made me very nervous.  It was a bit overwhelming for him at first, but the staff helped him through it.  He started playing and loved all the attention he received from the staff.  I used the web cam ALL the time and was thrilled to see them playing and having a ball.  It is a great feeling to see firsthand, they didn't feel like I abandoned them for a week, rather they were on a fun vacation themselves. I've been taking Nikko there for years and always VERY happy with the staff.  I'm so glad Tucker will fit right in next time he goes to camp!< /Text><Pics>None<//Pics>< rating>

< Text>
Camp Bow Wow is a nice place in Temecula to take your dog. If you are new, your dog gets a "review". The review takes three hours of your puppies time and only fifteen minutes of your time. You even get to watch your puppy interact with the other dogs. Even though the review takes three hours, your allowed to leave your dog for the day- basically giving you a free day of doggy care.

Leonidas, my puppy loved it there. It helped that he knew two other dogs, Samson and D. i had asked that my puppy be allowed to stay in the same room as Sam and D but due to his size, he was not. However, the package i recieved at the end of his doggy review day said that Leonidas had nap time with Sam and D.

When I am back in Temecula, Leonidas will be going to them!

Cons: alittle out of the way- Thank you GPS!

Pros: you get to monitor your puppy, you get a puppy package letting you know how he did and who he played!!

thanks for such a wonderfull time!</Text>

<review>I finally stopped by this place I've been wanting to try. I was greeted as I walked in asking if I needed any help with the menu. All food is organic and made in house. You walk up to the register, place your order and they deliver it to your table. Prices are reasonable and they offer vegetarian options as well.

I ordered the grass fed steak with one side. Food came out fairly quickly and the overall service was amazing. Brinton was awesome at helping me decide what to order.

The steak was flavorful and tender. I prefer med with a little pink in the center. Although the steak seemed well done, I still thought it was tasty. I wanted to try their in house drinks but I knew I wouldn't have room for a dessert if I did. I ordered cookies but was too full to continue.

I will definitely return and try the other items on the menu.< /review><pics>None< /pics>< Resp>

I used to order pizza here every Friday for game night and over half of my orders ended up wrong. I've had issues such as wrong/missing dipping sauces, wrong toppings and the one that usually bothers me is when I ask for Chicago cut and they give me regular. I've emailed the company and spoke to to the manager but I still received inaccurate orders. I finally gave up and decided to take my business elsewhere.<//Review>

< Rate>
3</Rate>
< review>
They are known for their dipping ramen. Their menu is concise and easy to pick from. The service is great and the food was prepared quickly. They have outdoor sittings available.

-1 star because they didn't follow any protocol of taking temperature or hand sanitization. When you pay with cards, you still have to sign on their touchscreen devices (making it unsanitary as they don't clean it after each use).  -1 because I don't think there's anything unique about this place. The flavor is average, the noodle is standard, and overall, sitting right on the benchmark.

Expect to pay between $18-25 per person. I'll be trying nearby restaurants first before considering returning.< /review>

<Review>Overview:
Did some research before coming here and decided to come to this location vs their annex location across the street.  Haven't had the annex location yet but very glad that we chose this one!  First off, can I just say that I appreciate a ramen shop that understands my late night ramen cravings and so they're open late?  We came here for second dinner at midnight and pretty much had the shop to ourselves.

Food:
I am a huge tsukemen fan so when I heard this place is known for their dipping ramen then I had to try it.  I immediately picked the cha siu tsukemen since it comes with the most food :P   The noodles were a great level of firmness, the chashu pork for tender, and the broth.... the broth was absolutely awesome and reminded me of some ramen shops I had in Japan.  I was really full afterwards!  To this day, I still day dream about it every now and then and plan to come back as soon as I can!< /Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><Resp>None< /Resp><GmapID>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>
< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
<Review>easily the best tsukemen you will find in SoCal, and probably a top contender for best tsukemen west of the Rockies.

fwiw, i only ever order the tsukemen when i come here. I'm sure their ramen is great, but the tsukemen is just that good.

the broth is velvety and sumptuous, the char siu is evanescently tender, and the noodles have a delightfully springy bite to them. squeeze the lime they give you over the noodles to add some brightness and acidity to cut through the richness.

the portion might seem small but a regular bowl of noodles and broth is a challenge for me (a fully grown man with a healthy appetite). with extra char siu (that is, in addition to the pieces already in the broth) and a seasoned egg, it's a veritable feast.

if you live in Southern California and like Asian food, you owe it to yourself to come here. undefeated.< /Review><username>Nimish Pratha<//username>< user_id>

<Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Text>
Went to this Noodle shop from recommendation from a you tube video.

This was our first time here and we wanted a nice hot bowel of noodles/ramen, because it was quite cool outside that evening.

We were so hungry and we both ordered Charlie tsukemen by mistake. The cold noodles were thick and delicious.  The slices of pork belly are amazing as well. The broth was a hot dipping broth in a separate bowl, also tasted good.

We both decided to dump the dipping sauce all over the noodles bowl to in order to avoid having to dip the noodles each time we took a bite to eat.

This combination was still good, but not what we wanted on the chilly evening.

Next time I am going to order the spicy ramen with level 3 heat.  That way I know we have ordered something served steaming hot.  The normal way we like or orders.

Going back soon!</Text>

<Text>Greetings,
Attached is the receipt of my purchase to emphasize truth to my claims of having dined-in at Tsujita LA Artisan Noodle. First off, I had horrible experience eating here and will not recommend you eat here. The noodles were cold. Initially, I dismissed this as the style of the noodles early on as I felt this place warranted my patience and understanding of the dish. However, I was wrong because then the broth was cold, which is an understatement to the reality that no heat at all radiated from this highly reviewed restaurant.

Most importantly, I failed to accept this reality of having a bad experience as I like to remain optimistic until the server, Saki, confused me and my partner's order, henceforth, destroying the last remaining shred of patience and our commitment to wanting to have a good time. We did not enjoy a peaceful and delicious meal. We were provided a completely different broth after asking for the same broth, which ruined our entire meal as the flavor was completely different from our initial order. At no point was it communicated and presented to us an option to pay more for the same broth prior to the servers mistake that ruined our meal. When presenting with the facts, the server did indeed state that it was a different broth. Our first was pork/fish based and the second provided was soley fish based to the point that you can actually smell fish. One confronted with the evidence the server realizing her mistake lied to us stating that what we initially ordered was exactly the same. It was not the same. A child could see the difference in color let alone the taste. We are not blind. In light of Saki's rhetoric and delivery of speech, we now felt profoundly offended. To top it off, she remained committed to ignore her mistake and force us to pay. We were not presented an opportunity of a new dish but, an additional cost as a reprimand to a mistake we did not make.

In sum, I have not felt such dissatisfaction from eating somewhere in my 25 years in Los Angeles that I felt appalled to continue the conversation with a server with no customer service skills. To her defense, closing time neared at the restaurant and I felt an urgency from the servers to want to leave. It being the end of the day I completely understand the feeling of dread of wanting to go home. However, this carelessness cost me and my partner our time, money, and energy that we can never reclaim. I am grateful for the privilege to having identified a future chain of restaurants I will never dine in ever again and recommend. It pains me to write this. <Rating>5</Rating><review>Excellent ambiance. Easy to find right on a well trafficked corner. Plenty of outdoor and indoor seating. Waitstaff was very friendly and accommodating of questions. Your entire party must be present in order to be seated due to covid rules so just be advised on that. Food was excellent and the drinks were standard fare for a nicer Japanese restaurant. <user_name>Candice Lee</user_name><Time>1513102536429</Time>< rating>
5</rating>
< Review>
One of my favorite spots for tsukemen ! I love coming here and it's definitely worth the wait. It often looks bad but the tables go in and out pretty quickly.

I would recommend getting their tsukemen upon visiting - I usually get it with the char siu and the boiled egg. They give you a huge bowl of noodles with a small bowl of thick thick delicious broth to dip your noodles in ! Be careful, it's quite salty to just be sipping on by itself.

How I usually like to eat it is with extra extra likes and if you like spicy, they have a jar of pickles greens that goes really well with the noodles. SO SO good.

Once you're done with the meal, feel free to ask them to thin out your tsukemen soup with some broth to end the meal.

10/10 would recommend. Although some people have said it may be a little salty, I think it's definitely worth trying.<//Review>

< name>
Brandon Chacon<//name>
<Date>1601302311039</Date>< Rating>
3<//Rating>
<text>I was really looking forward to this authentic experience that was talked up by family and friends. My experience was rather mixed. We went with a party of 4 and although the line was a decent wait, COVID times meant not too many others were fighting for tables. The outdoor seating was decent for the size of the place and the QR code menu was an interesting way to stay sanitary.
We all ordered the standard go-to tsukemen which others recommended. I can see now why this ramen isn‚Äôt for everyone. Yes, the noodles are rather cold, and the broth that you dip in is supposed to counter that, but the broth needed to be hotter to do so. The noodles and the pork were great. Pork chashu is supposed to be that salty so no complaints there. Noodles were clearly authentic and had great texture.
The broth was something else. If you are sensitive to fishy smell/taste then you should stay away. The tsukemen is not advertised as being a fish based broth, but it was truly reeking of some sea-based product. Think fish gravy. Cutting the flavor with the added limes or even with requested chili on the side did little to mitigate that taste. One of our party‚Äôs members took one bite and was immediately put off eating any further.
I‚Äôd like to say that it ended there, but sadly several of our party members also suffered massive stomach pains the following night/day. Japanese food has never done that to me before, authentic or otherwise. We went out of our way to try this recommendation, unfortunately I won‚Äôt be passing the recommendation along. Be careful of hype.</text>< pics>

< user_name>
Jared Cohee< /user_name>
< Time>
1544554737497<//Time>
< rate>
4</rate>
< review>
JAPAN üáØüáµ
Eat the World LA review:
Not to be outdone by downtown's Little Tokyo, the small area on Sawtelle Blvd with many Japanese businesses became known as Little Osaka. This apparently rubbed the wrong way on the folks that were not specifically from Osaka and eventually the strip was rebranded as Sawtelle Japantown, a decidedly boring name.
¬∞
Anyone that loves Japanese food, and especially ramen, is supposed to come here for their famous tsukemen, tonkotsu broth that is simmered for a full 60 hours, sweetened and thickened by seafood. Tsukemen is served as components, you do the addition and subtraction yourself, usually dipping the noodles as you go. If you need more broth, it can be refilled. Ajitama tsukemen is broth with a seasoned soft boiled egg, it is also available plain or with char siu. After you finish your noodles, ask for them to pour in some light broth to the dipping sauce and enjoy the resulting soup on its own.
¬∞
The standard bowl of tonkotsu ramen is also available here for those that prefer everything at one time.<//review>

<user>116007422790857032117</user>< username>
Michael Morrow<//username>
<time>1557642981330</time>< rating>
5</rating>
< review>
After having some at an amazing little shop in Shinjuku, Tokyo, I was really craving some tsukemen (dipping noodles) once I was back in the states. I found this place had it, so I made the drive from Phoenix this weekend to give it another try. I was worried it would be an Americanized version, but I think they got it just right. The dipping broth is rich and thick like I remember and the noodles were great. I was a little confused at the end since I remembered the shop in Tokyo having insulated pitchers of soup stock (dashi) spread along the counter for pouring into your leftover dipping broth to make it thinner and more like a drinkable soup, but there was no pitchers on the tables they had here, and instead I was directed to this little "tsukemen" sauce bottle on the table... When I rephrased it, they took my bowl up to the counter where I finally saw the same sort of insulated pitcher I remembered from Japan. Once I had the bowl back with the warm soup it was just as tasty and made me feel happy to have made the trip from Phoenix. Thanks, all, for satisfying my craving! I hope tsukemen soon spreads across the US!</review>

<userid>115960942273201366942< /userid><Time>1484684706555< /Time><name>McKay ‚ÄúOnetricked‚Äù Zabriskie</name><Resp>None< /Resp>< GmapID>
0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//GmapID>
< Text>
This place is Cozy and arguably the best Ramen in LA. The Annex is small and easy to miss but it is definitely a hidden gem. There are only about 15-18 seats here  so there is usually a wait, but they take your order and start it so by the time you sit down, your order is almost finished. Be prepared for a little strange smell as you wait.

The Ramen is really high quality and thick. The broth is thick and rich and bursting with flavor. It's goes well with the thick noodles. To top it off, the pork just falls apart in your mouth and makes the experience. I got a soft boiled egg to go with it and it is a must have.

Despite being so busy, the customer service here is as great as could be expected! They always keep your glass full and occasionally check up on you. I highly recommend trying this place at least once. If you don't, you will miss out.< /Text>

<user_name>Serina Gee<//user_name>< Date>
1520287296492<//Date>
<rating>4< /rating>< Review>
I think Tsujita would hold it's own in Tokyo, though I wouldn't wait more than 45 minutes. Came on a Friday night and it took maybe an hour, as the restaurant is small. The meal itself is super filling. I recommend getting tsukemen with chashu and ajitama. It was my family's first time trying tsukemen and they enjoyed the new experience.

Don't forget to get the soup wari! Basically, the dipping broth is too rich to drink (simmered for 60 hours!), so at the end of the meal, you dilate it with broth water such that it's drinkable!<//Review>

< userid>
107063077542687998922<//userid>
<user_name>Jobie Low</user_name>< date>
1557174550980</date>
<rating>5< /rating>< review>
Visiting LA and friends pointed to Tsujita LA as a must - go for noodles.. When we get there I realize that it serves tsukemen... whaaa..? It's noodles cooked that you dip in the broth. Huh? Why can't we be Slurp-happy and eat ramen?

But tsukemen is a better way to go. You savor the broth-seafood origins that both coats the noodles and becomes a vehicle to taste all the intricacies usually lost while slurping ramen. They want you to try the broth first, then try it with a squeeze of lime, then enjoy with various additions-mine was a a jar of  turnip-like stuff that added heat in a very earthy way. I want to know where I can buy this stuff!

When you're done with the noodles they come around and ask if you want to add broth to your soup. The original soup is very thick, almost undrinkable, but adding broth makes it a very pleasant ending to a great lunch.

The hostess is very nice, sensing we were newbies( it's that obvious?) but explaining how to eat tsukemen for the millionth time in a way that we weren't a bother.

If you go, go early, we walked in at 11amand when we left at11:45 it was like the first showing of Avengers "Endgame." Well worth the first visit, looking forward to the next!< /review>

< Text>
This place was really good, but for being touted as one of the "best in the world", I had higher expectations.

Personally, I didn't care for the service style of separate noodles that needed to be dipped in the broth. The noodles tasted very average to me, but the broth was really good. However, the overall dining experience left me underwhelmed.

Prepare to wait for a long time, even at 10pm on a weeknight.</Text>

<rate>3<//rate>< Text>
Would love to give this place a higher review, but honestly, I don't think I could ever give anything more than 3 stars for a wait this long! Nothing is worth waiting hours and hours in line for!!

That being said, their tsukemen definitely is the way to go here. I've had tsukemen at so many other places in LA but nothing tops the unique consistency and taste that you get here.

I like the cheat and halfway through my bowl, I'll just dump the sauce/soup into the bowl of noodles because dipping is hard work! :P

Make sure you are mindful of your parking when you come here as the meters have limits and there are plenty of cops that will come by and enforce them!</Text>

< review>
I have been going here, almost weekly, for 6 years.  The Ajitama Tsukemen is my favorite thing to eat in all of LA, make sure to put a little spicy mustard leaf in your noodles.  Everyone is so nice here.  Since COVID, I have been getting the soup togo for the first time.  It takes them between 5-10 minutes to get it ready, you can order directly by just walking up.  They also sell Asahi beer to accompany your meal.  Still amazing food, but I am really missing seeing everyone there and listening that funky music, (pretty sure the music has changed once in 7 years, haha).  I'll be back, as always!  Keep kicking a** Tsujita and staff!< /review>

<Review>I can‚Äôt go back to regular ramen anymore.

I really wish dipping ramen/tsukumen was more popular outside of LA! The intense broth/‚Äúdip‚Äù flavours were perfect for me and my meathead bros. It was like a seafood gravy, and the thick, chewy noodles were so springy they reminded me of jajangmyeon. The ‚Äústages‚Äù of eating it wasn‚Äôt just a gimmick either, it was lightening the flavours so you wouldn‚Äôt feel like death after! ALSO: the soft boiled egg was perfectly boiled, the yolk was legit like liquid gold and just barely settled.

There‚Äôs generally a wait time and no real good area to lounge, but there are plenty of places to check around while you wait. Since it‚Äôs LA, expect to park on the street and pay for the meter (which is actually free on weekends!).

It‚Äôs a lovely different way to enjoy ramen, and probably my favourite way from now on.<//Review></record></dataset><record>

<Name>Nathaniel Arias-Velez</Name><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOqcbrIr13gMRPcD4RPXeBGL-cf-5QcyhTIg-Wx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures>< Resp>

<Text>Listen. It's worth it. Everything you've ever heard? True and then some. This place most absolutely smacks. The quality that goes into this food will open your eyes and make you realize how blasphemous instant  noodle is.

Now yes, this dipping noodle. I'm an avid ramen lover and didn't necessarily understand the concept behind dipping the noodle. Why not just put it all together and call it ramen?

Well, the broth is actually very flavorful. So flavorful that if you take a spoonful, it's too much to enjoy for long. Dipping the noodle and consuming (slurping is best) immediately after the dip, will be just want you need to enjoy it best. And yes, you should enjoy a couple of noodles and then add the lime. It somehow does an amazing job at subtly attaching itself to the noodle even after being dipped. Top it all off by asking for some extra hot water and you've just enjoyed some of the best noodle you'll ever have.

While here, I ordered the Cha Siu Tsukemen and shared it. It was so good I had to return to order for myself. The second time I still ordered the Cha Siu Tsukemen with extra noodles and extra egg. I regret nothing.

I can't wait to be reunited with this place again.<//Text>< Date>

< name>
Jovani Cardenas</name>
<date>1559418898155</date>< rating>
5<//rating>
< text>
First Star: Is the location neat? Yes. The turnover is fast but a staff member is always on hand immediately to clear and wipe tables.

Second Star: Is the staff friendly? Yes.

Third Star: Is the service prompt? Yes. Once you've braved the line outside your food comes quickly. The staff is also conscious of taking orders from those in line to make the service move even quicker. Very efficient.

Fourth Star: Is the product/service satisfactory? Yes. Absolutely. The tsukemen broth is hearty and rich. The cold dipping noodles make a fantastic companion to the hot broth, keeping their springy chew until you're ready to dip. The char siu is tender and full of flavor.

Fifth star: Is the price acceptable? Yes. Always worth it to drop in.< /text>

< review>
See the red chili‚Äôs in the picture. Those chili‚Äôs are just one of the tiny nuances that makes this ramen one of the best. We arrived on a chilly saturday evening to have this ramen and I was pleasantly surprised to see about 30 odd people waiting to get in the restaurant. We opted for patio seating since the wait time was much less in the cold weather. Add 11.50 the ramen is priced reasonably but you do need to add 1.50 soft boiled eggs in order to make this ramen worth it. The broth itself is rich and the pork belly is soft and juicy. The best part about their ramen is that you can get extra broth for free. My girlfriend ended up having the vegan ramen which although tasted a little bit like pho but was worth it for her. Would definitely come back to try the tsukemen.< /review>

<user_name>ÏÜêÏ§ÄÌëú</user_name>< text>
Before my visit, I'd never tried tsukemen and wasn't really a fan of Japanese ramen. However, the ajitama tsukemen here may have changed both of those statements. Well, at least in terms of dipping ramen. I thought the noodles were pleasantly chewy while the broth was thick and not overly salty. The soft-boiled egg and pork were as one would expect from a restaurant that specialized in ramen. My only complaint about the dish was that the broth was a little warmer than room temperature at best, and I'd prefer it to be much hotter. Overall, I left the restaurant feeling satisfied by both the taste and the portion, which is something I'd never experienced before upon finishing a meal at a ramen restaurant.<//text>

<user_id>115641290493930413752</user_id>< user_name>
Michael Sirounian< /user_name>
< Date>
1502019732153< /Date>
< rating>
5</rating>
< Text>
Pretty damn yummy. Spend the extra dollar and get the tsukemen with the soft boiled egg which was perfectly cooked by Ramen standards. It's expensive for what tsukemen is, but the delicious taste of the soup will have me comming back soon. The soup had these bits of really salty meat which I think went perfectly with the noodles, especially if used sparingly. The soup got cold quick due to the nature of tsukemen so I can't complain about that. It was a bit loud in there on a Thursday night, so i only recomend this place if you want to eat Ramen and nothing else. If you wanna talk to your date or whatever, get it out of your system while you're waiting outside becuase there can be a waiting list when busy. Seating is a bit cramped but I guess if they had less seats then the wait times would be longer. My only complaint is that there isn't more space for this wonderful restaurant to supply the demand for delicious Ramen. I wouldn't call this a traditional Ramen restaurant but I don't think it's what they're going for anyway. They provide a lime to twist over your noodles which is odd but I'm digging it. There's also hand fans at every table which is nice if you start sweating from the hot soup.</Text>

<rate>3<//rate>< Review>
The Tsukmen with Pork is incredibly filling and more salty then I like...although not so salty that I couldn't eat it. I wasn't the only person asking for a to-go container, as it was so filling and too good to leave behind. Staff is super, friendly and willing to explain the menu (there are actual instruction cards at each seat, advising how to eat this traditional food). Lines are long virtually all the time, so be prepared to wait, particularly on the weekends. For the food I'd give 4 starts, but...the entire facility could use a good scrubbing, the tables are sticky and restrooms poorly maintained, hence the 3 stars.<//Review>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
Tsujita is one of my favorite places in LA to get ramen and tsukumen. Their broth (which is the pillar of all good ramen) is rich and flavorful. You can taste the dedication that's been made to making the broth. If you're getting ramen, you can select thin, regular or thick noodle depending on what you like. It's slightly pricey, but you definitely get the quality you pay for.<//review>

<username>Yutack Kang< /username>< date>
1521567237317<//date>
<rate>5<//rate><Review>Delicious tsukemen! Service was fast and friendly. Don't hesitate to ask how to eat the tsukemen, the waiters love to help and there's also an instructional sheet for first timers.

Some tips:
1. it's totally fine to slurp, it's actually encouraged
2. if you're looking for spicy, add a spoonful of pickled mustard (karashi takana) onto the noodles. it's very spicy so add only a little at a time
3. You can add the lime at anytime, I like adding it with about a third of the noodles left. This way you can experience the different flavors throughout the meal.
4. Once you're done with your noodles, they'll ask if you want 'wari' (beef broth). This way you can slurp hot broth to complete the meal

Cash only with ATM inside< /Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNcH4NO9vTMFd5fdDDZjiS24Y4OYaDHB1HREn10=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPireKFtpIcOztjUGVTgNt9jbfmoJNGu6FHyUBK=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures>< Response>

<user>106914396020495186174</user><username>Danh Nguyen<//username><time>1557077724312</time><rate>5< /rate>< Review>
There are 2 Tsujita Ramen across each other, the one right at the intersection accept CASH ONLY and the soup not good as the other location across the street. Tsujita Annex is accepting credit card and the broth to me taste better, spicier. Both locations are busy during peak lunch/dinner hours, you could wait in line for 30 mins and longer for a table of 2. The space/table is small, you are literally next to each other and in other face! There are table/booth for larger group otherwise you have to share sitting. Pricey but typical in West LA, expect $15-$20 for each bowl of ramen after tax.< /Review>

</record></dataset><record>
<userid>114260703412621045091<//userid><name>Leah Vergel de Dios</name>< time>
1549653759149</time>
<rate>5< /rate>< Review>
In my opinion, this is the best place to get ramen in the area--which is really saying something, considering all the options within 20 yards! Simple menu, small interior, and no-fuss service and seating. it's cash only, as well, though there is an ATM in the back, make sure you bring cash if you don't want to pay the fees.

You'll want to be prepared to wait, whether you're there before it opens for lunch/dinner or just walking up. There's always a crowd of people standing outside, and there's a list that has the parties in front of you that you can add your name to. If it's not raining, I would say it doesn't matter at all if you're seated inside or outside. The last couple of times I've been there, the wait has been around half an hour. Your whole party has to be present to be seated.

If you like spicy, the level 3 spicy Tonkatsu is the best! It's a lingering heat, not burning, so you can happily eat through the entire bowl, navigating through an abundant amount of red peppers and green onions. The meat is super tender and flavorful, and the noodles (best purchased "hard" out of all the options!) are firm and taste fresh. I always have trouble picking between that and the Ajitama Tsukemen, which is the dipping ramen--definitely an experience on its own. It comes with thicker noodles and broth than the ramen that comes with the noodles in the broth, and the texture is unbelievable. Extra limes for the noodles are a must, and so is getting the lighter broth at the end to enjoy the entire experience.

Overall such a great spot in a great location. For sure worth the wait, and even though it's super busy you never feel like you're being rushed; great experience with great food every time.</Review>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//Gmap_id>< review>
CASH ONLY!

I like the noodles here better then the actual Tsujita restaurant across the street. I usually get the tsukemen ( dipping the noodles into a hot broth). There is usually a wait to be seated - it's a very small place. They will only take your order when your whole party is there. Upon ordering, when they call you to sit they've already begun cooking your food so you'll get it, usually, within 5 minutes of being seated. Amazing fatty broth - don't expect to do too much after you eat here.</review>

< text>
My husband and I had never had dipping ramen noodles before, but this experience has changed ramen for us forever. The balance between the cold noodles and the hot dipping broth made the perfect ready to eat temperature. The flavors of the broth and the lime on the noodles complimented each other perfectly. I don't think regular ramen will ever satisfy us again. The staff were all very friendly in helping us and talking with us about the experience.</text>

<Review>The tsukemen is very similar to the ones you will find in Japan. I would describe it as a diluted version of it. Tsukemen dipping sauce is traditionally more pungent and flavorful. The noodles are cooked perfectly but I don't recommend following their instructions about coating your noodles in lime. The lime easily overpowers the dipping sauce. It typically would not but since it is diluted it is easily overpowered. I give it a five star because it is the most closely authentic tsukemen I've found in the US.<//Review>< gmapID>

<Name>Ijun Lai<//Name>< Text>
DELICIOUS!! The wait was 20 minutes which is really difficult for me to do because I get hangry. My friend was a little worried that I would rip her to pieces so we bought a snack nearby to hold me over. It was worth the wait. They take your order while you're waiting in line so that by the time you sit down, your meal is ready for you. GENIUS. I had the tsukemen with pork and added a soft boiled egg. I also added a ton of garlic--not that the broth needed it, but because I love garlic. These noodles were a perfect amount of chewiness and thickness. The pork was unbelievably tender, and so great with the slivers of green onions. I wish I lived in LA so I could come here all the time. The wait staff is super nice as well. Loved everything!< /Text>

112922789643288943710< /user_id>
< name>
Benjamin Wan< /name>
< Time>
1530572810193< /Time>
< Rating>
4</Rating>
<text>Legit tsukemen ramen! This will leave you full and satisfied for sure. I used to never enjoy ramen all that much because I'm never full afterwards like I am eating pho...but oh boy, this place is quite the opposite.

We ordered the Tsukemen Ramen with Chaw Siew. They give you a solid amount of thick and perfectly cooked ramen noodles. I'm a sucker for the thick noodles, thin ones just don't do it as much for me. Next to the heaping bowl of noodles is their awesome creamy and rich broth.

With Tsukemen, you dip the noodles into the broth and then consume. The broth isn't meant for you to slurp on like other ramen bowls, which makes this a somewhat fun experience eating. The broth itself has scattered pieces of meat inside amongst other things and very flavorful overall.

The ramen also came with a softboiled egg which is obviously very tasty. We ordered sake on the side as well.

Overall a pretty good place to get yourself a bowl of Tsukemen Ramen and a nice family ambiance inside. Highly recommended! There is apparently also another restaurant that is EXACTLY the same across the street to help with the popularity and wait time.< /text><Pics>None<//Pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

Tsujita is known for their tsukemin, which is a bowl of ramen noodles that are dipped into a rich, concentrated broth before each bite.  After finishing the noodles, you are offered the option to mix a clear broth into the rich broth so that you can drink up the rest of it as a soup. <review>Mixed review for me. This was my first experience with Tatsu ramen. The flavor was very good, but the broth was room temperature...once mixed with the cold noodles, it was cold mess. Not a fan.

I also ordered a spicy ramen which was excellent. Piping hot and a wonderful aroma and flavor. Chili peppers added additional heat, but not too much. I ordered a spiciness of 2 out of 3.

Bad part - server spilled a quarter of the piping hot ramen all over my leg. She helped to get napkins and clean her mess, but did not compensate me with a discount or any other offer. Not an ideal way to treat your customers.

All in all, a good noodle house, but nothing out of the ordinary or exciting. Small, cramped quarters without any charm or pizazz.</review></record>

< Name>
Linda Ly<//Name>
< Time>
1465249873556< /Time>
<rate>5<//rate>< Text>
Tip before coming here :) It's cash only.
My second time eating here and both experiences were great! You usually have to sign your name and wait, but most people are pretty good about eating and leaving, so, it doesn't take too long for seats to open. I've waited no more than an hour, and it's worth the wait if so! The staff does get busy running around but are always willing to help and with friendly service too. I definitely recommend eating tsukemen with chashuu. So good!! They have a cute illustration that shows you the proper way of eating it and the waiting staff can explain too if you ask. Remember lime in the noodles! Then dip noodles into the broth. I would definitely recommend eating here if you want to try delicious, authentic tsukemen.<//Text>

<date>1523321073081< /date><Rate>4</Rate><text>Have been meaning to try this place on Sawtelle for some time. Finally bit the bullet and went to Tsujita for my usual Sunday noodle lunch with my girlfriend.  I must say the food was great! I had the spicy pork ramen (have forgotten the official menu listing) and was pleasantly surprised at the firey heat that the level 3 spicyness brought with it. I mean by simply looking at the bowl you would think it were a normal pork ramen bowl, but one spoonful of that broth will let you know that looks can be deceiving. My girlfriend had the tsukemen (sp?), and was very happy with her plate.

Overall, this place is another great addition to the cuisine offered here in Little Osaka/Sawtelle. Be cautious as this restaurant is VERY popular so be prepared to wait if during peak hours. The taste is well worth the wait, and the pricing is fair.  Can't wait to return.<//text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Resp>

<user_id>118340948866946722024</user_id><name>Chad K< /name>< time>

< rating>
5<//rating>
<review>This is the place that introduced me to tsukemen - thick, cold, chewy noodles dipped in gravy-thick hot soup. Oh buddy, this is the good stuff. As I understand it each of their locations features a different style of broth (hence why there is a second restaurant across the street). If I understood my server correctly this location is fish and pork, and the Annex is just pork. Both are amazing (but I do prefer the Annex overall). Slightly more expensive than most ramen-ya but definitely worth it. Blows all of the hipster competitors out of the water. Don't forget to get soup wari when your broth gets low.

Some caveats: Cash only, but has an ATM. No vegetarian options as far as I know.</review>< pics>

<Text>Decent place for ramen. Expect to wait at least 30 mins for a table. Food is served quickly once you sit down. I had the char siu tsukumen. The pork is very soft and tender and the noodles are cooked well. You dunk the noodles into the pork broth and then slurp it up. The broth did a great job warming up the noodles initially, but quickly became luke warm and didn't do so well warming up the noodles after about 5 mins of slurping. The broth is full of flavor, but very concentrated. Once you are done with the noodles, ask the staff to thin out the broth to make it drinkable.< /Text>< Response>

<userid>106540439831562617904< /userid><Review>I love this area, so many different restaurants that I want to try them all.

First things first, they take your order outside so that the food comes as quick as possible when you sit down.

Since there is only about 20 seats they try to push customers in and out! (reminds me of my server days at a Japanese Ramen Restaurant)

This is an extension of the original restaurant across the street.

Regular size bowls were 10-12, and large were 14-16

The large size is huge! enough to share with someone so you can enjoy other items on the menu. OR get 2 large and split between three people.

The Char - Siu pork is tasty! head across the street for dessert at block heads! Sawtelle is like better than Little Toyko at this point!< /Review>< Gmap_id>

< Name>
Annie Lin</Name>
<date>1408394702552<//date><Rate>4< /Rate>< Text>
I finally got to try Tsujita! The ramen here is quite delicious. I can't say if its the same, similar, totally off as from the original Tsujita but I did enjoy my meal here. I got the Tsukemen with soft boiled egg (and asked for less salty from reading other reviews) . The broth is VERY oily - it made me feel super full for the rest of the day- I don't recommend eating this often but it definitely is a treat once in awhile. I believe the spicy sauce was what made the broth, mmm my tummy is just dreaming about how delicious it was :) The soft boiled egg wasn't really soft - boiled, I usually like it runny but some people may prefer it the way Tsujita makes it. The wait is long though, definitely be prepared!<//Text>

100366113117526980111</userid>
< username>
Jen H< /username>
<time>1513122450249</time><rating>5< /rating><review>I don't want to overcomplicate this and write a super long review because it's pretty simple: DELICIOUS TSUKEMEN.

Note that Tsujita has two locations pretty much across each other. This is  the ANNEX. Both are great but if you prefer a fattier, richer broth then I highly recommend the ANNEX over the OG location. And yes, the line is equally long for both restaurants.

If you go during off hours, you'll get a chance to avoid the line but if you want to eat during normal lunch/dinner hours, then prepare to wait (like 1-2 hours). Also this place is CA$H only. The menu is pretty simple, highly highly recommend getting the tsukemen. The portion doesn't seem too big but it is really filling, because of that I recommend getting the regular size and then getting an a delicious tuna rice bowl add on :) Taste the broth alone and then add in a generous heaping of the chili and garlic because it tastes sooooooooo good all together. The tsukemen broth is thick, fatty, rich, savory and perfect for dipping your noodles in!

If you're a fan of noodles (especially chewy thicker noodles) then you have to try this place! It's worth the wait.</review>< Pictures>

< name>
Jennifer Lo<//name>
< Date>
1510338496880<//Date>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Text>
Voted number one in LA and it lived up to the hype! The ramen was so good. I ordered the tsukemen and the tuna don. The tsukemen is the dipping noddles where they give you a bowl of thick concentrated broth and you dip eat bite into the broth. The broth had a strong bonito flavor and wasn't overly salty. The noodles were also perfectly chewy. I ordered the tsukemen with the pork slices, but the normal bowls already have pieces of pork mixed into the broth so don't worry about not having meat. After you're finished with your noodles, you can ask for broth to be poured into your bowl in order to drink the tsukemen broth. This is one of the best bowls that I have had! It's alway great because it is open till late night!< /Text>

1486020304002</date>
< Rate>
4< /Rate>
< Text>
Awesome joint for Tsukemen aka dipping ramen. You can add wari (extra broth) at the end for free. Table condiments are fresh garlic and chili flakes. In my person opinion, this place has a low noise level, which is great if you want to focus on the delicious bowl of noodles and watch the chef's expertly prepare them. No distractions, basically! The flavor of the broth and bite to the noodle will make you come back. Many ramen shops serve Tsukemen, but Tsujita sets the standard. Try their other locations for broth variations and table condiment variations. Other locations also have full menus with plenty of delicious Japanese options.</Text>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f</Gmap_id><pictures>None< /pictures><userid>113386839400931194984</userid><username>Jackie Yeap< /username><Date>1506495341176</Date>< review>
First time having Tsukemen and this did not disappoint. Although not exactly ramen, I finally found something that I would placed over my favorite ramen joint (Santouka).

I liked the option to add garlic and spice powder to customize the taste of the broth to your liking. Since I like spicy food, I spammed the spice powder and it was all worth it. Noodles definitely stood out as it was nice and bouncy to the chew.

It would be better if the broth can be a lot hotter so that it doesn't go cold a few minutes into the meal. But I think that may be how tsukemen is supposed to be so nothing much to do there.< /review>

<text>his place seem really popular when I heard about it then once I tried it not sure if its really worth the drive from one part of L.A. to the other side for dinner at this place. I had the popular Char Siu Tsukemen Ramen. The broth was really salty and the noodles were cold even after dipping it in the broth to eat. The waitress told me that after I finish the ramen they can pour some hot water for the broth then you can drink it like a soup. I felt like this ramen was a lot of work to eat so I just pour some of the broth all over the bowl with the char siu and ramen so it was easier to eat especially if you're not good with chopsticks.

I found the chopsticks to be a struggle when some places don't have chopsticks that grip the food easily. I got my blouse dirty from the broth splashing on it. I suggest you don't wear nice clothes if you really want to eat with the chopsticks and am not good at using them. Plan on paying for parking if you dine on Sawtelle Blvd. Don't park at a meter when it might only be limited to 1 hour parking.</text><Pics>None< /Pics>< resp>

<Time>1493695794443< /Time><Review>Too rich for my blood

Normally I'm a huge fan of rich flavors, really though, I stand in front of restaurants with a giant foam finger with dollar signs ($$$) on it...a true fan of richness.  But I'm also like Forrest Gump, "I'm not a smart man, but I know what flavor is..."  I just don't get it, why is there 736 UCLA students waiting out front every time I drive by? Don't you guys have to study or something?  When I was in college the only ramen I could afford was in a plastic bag ("m√¨ g√≥i" in Vietnamese).

Let me tell you where this rich flavor is coming from...

I ordered two ramen bowls because I'm a freakin' fatty.  Side note...I was called into a meeting at some hotel room last month and it was my whole family there with TV cameras for a fatty intervention.  I tried running but my thighs cramped up from the stress my stomach was putting on it and fell straight to the ground.

Back to the story...I took one of the bowls home to finish for my fatty midnight meal, put the rich "broth" into the fridge and when I took it out like 75% of it was coagulated fat! Enjoy kids.  Eat up and go study.<//Review><Pictures>None< /Pictures><user>103741301531365324072</user></record>

<userid>115058242070246842241< /userid>< name>
J</name>
< Date>
1447950412541<//Date>
<rating>3<//rating>< review>
I can understand why others like it so much. It's very flavorful and the noodles are what I would consider a step up from the supplier that the vast majority of places get their noodles from. But for me it's just far too heavy. Both the ramen and tsukemen feel like I'm ingesting liquified fat. The tsukemen is probably more enjoyable because you control the amount of broth and it is actually cleaner despite being thicker.<//review>

< user_id>
111694869338945346346</user_id>
< username>
Nick Degani<//username>
<Time>1476368126524<//Time><rating>4<//rating>< text>
If you're tired of Shinsengumi or Daikokuya, give Tsujita a try. For starters it's dipping noodles rather than traditional soup noodle. Do mind the line though; I'd recommend coming at non peak hours... Or if you have immense luck, come whenever.

So it's simple, come in, order the Tsukemen as that's what they're known for. The dipping broth and ramen come in separate bowls and may confuse you initially but take a look at the eating instruction manuel if it's your first time here or ask a waiter. Get extra limes and apply to the broth as needed. I enjoyed the ramen texture and the broth but be prepared for an oily broth. The meat was wonderfully made and practically melts in your mouth.

So the experience is probably novel for most people but it's definitely worth trying. The ramen is a little more on the expensive side though, and the broth cools down pretty quickly so it's best to eat as soon as you get your food. Cold ramen with cold broth is not pleasant at all. Oh and Tsujita is cash only so be prepared for that.</text>

<user_name>Matt Spindel</user_name><Time>1454562497128<//Time><Rate>5< /Rate><Text>This is for sure my favorite ramen shop! The complexity of the broth is out of this world! Perfectly balanced, it is truly sensational. Its served tsukemen style which is when the noodles come separate from the soup.

The broth is rich, fatty, spicy and is loaded with garlic. The noodles are thicker than standard ramen noodles. They are similar to udon but with the bite and texture of a ramen noodle.

If you want to know how this stands up to ramen in Japan, I can honestly say this is as good as the best places over there. I recently visited and made sure to eat ramen all over the country and Tsujita is as good as any of them. I have also taken many Japanese friends here and they confirm it's greatness!<//Text>< Pictures>

< Review>
Every time when I go to LA, this is a MUST GO place for me! Guys, if you like ramen, you should come here and TRY! I like their Tsukemen! It's my first time having ramen with the noodles on a bowl and the soup on the other. It makes the noodles less soggy when we eat.

Talking about the Tsukemen, the soup is really strong and rich, which is a good thing. But last time when I went there, the soup was a bit too salty, but other than that, everything was PERFECT! The overall presentation is nice and I like the idea that they have one big piece of fried seaweed on the noodles bowl, which is perfect for a person like me, since I don't really like to dip the whole seaweed into the soup.

I will definitely try their other ramen next time when I visit LA!<//Review>

<gmapID>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//gmapID><Date>1469520421466<//Date>< rating>

< rating>
3<//rating>
<review>If you Google search "best Ramen in Los Angeles" a great many lists and opinions will point toward Tsujita. The Tsujita Noodles Annex resides just across the street from Tsujita proper with a more limited menu, sticking only to the ramen and tsukemen that people clamor for.

I wanted to love the Annex. As a fan of good Japanese ramen, I felt no need to venture further west than Little Tokyo, but no longer could I ignore the much publicized Tsujita. Once you get to the Annex, you walk up, sign your name on the list and begin the wait. After about a half an hour, our order was taken, and another half an hour later, our name was being called to take our seat in the restaurant. The most notable experience when walking into the Annex is the smell. I wish it was a pleasant one, however, it was, for lack of a better term, funky......something like dead animal, stinky feet, and cheetos. Apparently, it is the slow drawing out of all the lovely flavors that go into the broth that brings out this smell.

Being that our order had been placed long before, our ramen was out shortly after being seated. The ramen came, a heaping serving of bean sprouts atop. Traditionally, I like to dive into the broth before anything else when eating ramen. After doing so, I had nothing else to think but, "this tastes like liquid fat." It's definitely flavorful, but as fatty and salty as could be. Once you mix everything together, char siu, bean sprouts, noodles, etc., you see how it all works together, but alone, the broth is impossible to enjoy. Unfortunately, there were a couple other issues. The additions to the ramen were cold. Obviously the bean sprouts were cold, but the char siu and egg were also, which created an odd experience.

In the end, I can appreciate the authenticity of Tsujita's ramen, but it has not persuaded me to move away from Daikokuya.< /review><Response>None<//Response><UserId.>110704716013971109471<//UserId.><pics>None< /pics><Gmap_id>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//Gmap_id><time>1447657329076<//time><username>Russell Saisho</username></record></dataset><record>

<Review>Tsujita LA is the most fascinating ramen place I've been to.  For one, they only serve ramen in this particular restaurant at lunch time (11am-2pm) and you should expect a line if you don't come a little before it opens.  The ramen here is very milky and heavy compared to the other choices around.  Some people will not like it because it really bogs down in your stomach but the flavor feels absolutely delicious and the noodles are just the right size.  All-in-all, a great choice for more experience ramen adventurers.  (Expect to pay around $10 along with the ability to slightly add more ingredients).  There are also some other noodle options that I didn't have a chance to explore.

Parking-wise, as usual in this area, look around the neighborhood nearby or on the street.<//Review><time>1396153313685</time>< userid>

<text>Having lunch here was actually unintentional. We originally intended on getting Tsujita Annex, where we're regulars. However, the wait for Tsujita Annex was 30+ minutes. We noticed that for once Tsujita LA had no line, so we decided there's a first for everything. We wondered across the street and were seated right away. < text>
I watched a documentary on Netflix where they had Tsukemen in Tokyo and I immediately wanted to have some. There's no other place in LA that's better known for their Tsukemen than Tsujita so my boyfriend and I made our way to Sawtelle in crazy traffic just to sample some.

I had heard that the wait on weekends can be pretty bad here and I can see why. The place is tiny. They did open the Tsujita Annex diagonally across the street but I have yet to peek in there. Since it was a weekday, we were able to grab the last 2 spots at the counter.

I had the Tsukemen while my boyfriend had the char siu ramen. I didn't care for the broth on their regular ramen too much. I prefer richer darker broth.

As for the Tsukemen, when I had the first bite, I was a little overwhelmed by the intense bonito flavor of the broth. It was very seafood-y. However, after I added lime to the noodle as recommended, the flavor balanced out extremely well. I thoroughly enjoyed my ramen to the last bite.

The restaurant is cash only. Parking used to be a pain but they have free valet parking with validation now. It's located behind the building.</text>

<review>First things first, you gotta know that the broth of the tsukemen and ramen is different than that of the Annex across the street. Lines are long, so I don't recommend going with a group bigger than 3. I went with a group of 8 and ended up waiting for 45 minutes even though our wait time was estimated to be only 20.

If you're coming here, try the tsukemen. The broth is more of a sauce that you dip the bouncy thick al dente noodles in. Get the 2nd option with the seasoned soft boiled egg. Squeeze the limes onto the soup to combat the dense fishy broth. At the end, ask for more broth (the actual soup) to dilute the dense sauce. Bring it home, and buy some ramen noodles from Nijiya to have yourself another meal ;)

I've tried the ramen, as well as the dons and I have to say that nothing compares to the tsukemen. The ramen broth was alright, but I hate the thin noodles that they use. I want my noodles to have a bite to them! The dons (Rice bowls) are $4 if you add them onto your entree, $6 otherwise.

How this differs from Annex: I can't finish a bowl of tsukemen because of how intensely fishy the broth is. I have as many friends who disagree and don't taste the fishiness as those who agree with my sentiments. I say taste the tsukemen from both restaurants. You can't go wrong with Tsujita!</review><pics>None<//pics><Response>None</Response><Gmap_id>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<time>1456788994785</time><userid>107715908908912865508< /userid><Text>Before you walk in the door, take note of the odor that exudes from this establishment. The rancid smell did not go unnoticed, but based on the Yelp reviews, we assumed that the smell must be coming from elsewhere, so we proceeded with caution.

They have two main Ramin options here - Tsukemen and Tonkotsu. The latter, the Tonkotsu, is a "specialty broth" that they make in house. There were four of us at dinner, three of us ordered a version of the Tonkotsu.

When the food arrived, the putrid smell overtook our table. Giving them the benefit of the doubt, I tasted the soup; however, it tasted just as badly as it smelled.

I knew immediately that I wasn't interested in eating another bite. When we politely requested an exchange, the manager, Shanon, was called over by our waitress. He rudely told me that they didn't offer any "refunds or exchanges." I explained this wasn't a refund, because I had not eaten the soup. < Text>
My all time favorite ramen spot. <name>Steven Vong< /name><time>1431234737093< /time><rating>5</rating><review>The best tsukemen I've ever had and some of the best ramen noodles in LA.

I always walk by this corner and see a ridiculous line at lunch (they only serve ramen at lunch). I was extra hungry and took my lunch break at 12:45 instead of 1 and there happened to be a free seat at the ramen bar so I knew this was an opportunity I couldn't pass up.

They have two options for ramen: Tsukemen (dipping) and traditional tonkotsu. From there you can choose chashu pork, no meat, eggs, etc. They also have some other rice dishes, but this artisan noodle stand is famous for the ramen so I went with the Chashu tsukemen.

My order came out quickly- they gave a generous portion of noodles and pork and a bowl of thick, saucey broth with a salty and perfectly gooey egg, bamboo shoots, and some pieces of meat. They also give you free lime and you can customize your broth with ginger, spice, tonkotsu sauce, and tsukemen sauce. The ramen was thick like spaghetti, firm and a little chilled. At first I dipped the noodles in the broth too long and it was way too salty. After swiftly swishing the noodles, I found the perfect balance between noodles and soup. The broth tasted even better after I ground some sesame seeds and added a little lime and tonkotsu sauce. The broth is what makes this place stand out from other ramen stands: they brew it for 60 hours with a wide variety of flavors that all combine to create an amazing savory sensation.

My only complaint is the price, a bowl of chashu tsukemen will run $15 without tip, but I was very satisfied with my meal and extra noodles and soup are only $1.50. Cash only. This place does live up to its hype and is simply a great ramen stand.</review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< response>
None<//response>

< text>
A much-belated review: After being thwarted at the regular Tsujita (they were closed filming a TV show or something) I noticed the Annex across the street and thought I'd give it a shot. I didn't even know this place existed, but I'm so glad I it was there! It was around 2pm-ish so the wait was minimal, thank goodness--I guess it can get kind of nutty, judging from the other reviews. It's a small but comfortable place, with clean modern (but not sterile) decor. I was a little surprised upon reading the menu--it was a lot more Chinese-influenced than what I was expecting. I got the regular ramen with the soft boiled egg and the Ikura (salmon roe) bowl. I was intrigued by the Tsukemen but wasn't in the mood for it at that moment. This ramen is definitely different than the standard Japanese ramen--it's much more bold and rich, with thick, curly, chewy noodles--yum! I can see why maybe some people wouldn't care for it, but it suited my Korean palate very well, especially with extra garlic and spicy seasonings. The Ikura bowl was good, with fresh roe and rice. Nothing mind-blowing but exactly what I was expecting so it satisfied. I was very full at the end of the meal, but knew I wanted to come back sooner than later. I need to try the tsukemen next time!<//text>

<gmap_id>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//gmap_id>< review>
Pros:
- creamy broth (so rich so delicious)
- dipping noodles for dinner (I think the original Tsujita only has this for lunch)
- tonkatsu ramen (I liked it better than the dipping ramen)

Cons:
- tiny tiny tiny restaurant means long wait for seating
- difficult to find parking
- pricey, especially if you choose add-ons (egg, green onions, seaweed, etc.)

Bottom line: I believe that a good bowl of ramen should be hearty and include an egg and other garnishings. If it's your first time, and you're feeling adventurous for tsukemen, try to get your friend to order tonkatsu ramen just in case you don't like the dipping style. That's how I ended up eating all of my dad's tonkatsu ramen and none of my dipping ramen...< /review>

< Text>
*Thumbs up*
After a 2-hour sweaty hike at Peters Canyon, my wife and I made the 1-hour long drive to LA just to have ramen here. It was definitely a spontaneous thing, because I was craving ramen and I kept seeing Tsujita popping up in reviews.

Luckily we got to Tsujita just shortly after the 11am opening time, because by the time we left the place was crawling with people waiting outside. Of course, I had to have the $14 bowl of tsukemen... and for my first time, it was pretty awesome. Having the two separate bowls was a bit odd at first, but it came natural after a few slurps and honestly it made the ramen eating experience that much more fun.

Both the noodles are broth are #1 in my book, thus far. The noodles had a great chew and consistency, and just perfectly sucked up the broth. The broth is very thick (viscous is the fancy word being thrown around) and heavily concentrated in flavor. Although it was mostly pork based, the broth is just so heavy that the lime squeeze on the noodle is essential to cut through it all.

The chashu is more of the thick cut variety with the layers of white fat still visible. I thought it tasted great, especially after dipping it in the broth. The neon orange, ooey gooey yolk from the egg was just #yolkporn at its finest. Yes, that was a hashtag.

*Thumbs down*
Yep, $14 for a bowl of ramen is pretty darn high and I think the highest I've ever paid for a bowl of ramen. I think this tsukemen is fine for the occasional splurge. Taking it easy on the arteries and the wallet, I can't imagine eating it on a regular basis. Cash only is irksome -- it's not like this place is dirt cheap. They need to get with the times and accept credit card.</Text>

<Rating>5</Rating><Review>Visiting from the Bay area where most ramen places are just decent, I had very high expectations for Tsujita. The wait wasn't bad, about 30-45 mins on a Sunday afternoon. The shops around the area are fun to browse while you're waiting.

My friend and I both tried the tonkatsu ramen. OMG dat broth. So fatty, sooo GOOD. The char siu was also amazingly tender and delicious. The only con was the egg was a little overcooked. But I'll overlook that in this case, since the rest of the bowl was pure perfection. Best ramen I've had so far.

I will definitely be back, especially to try the Tsukemen next time!

Service was great. CASH only!<//Review><pictures>None<//pictures><Response>None<//Response><Gmap_id>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<userid>100934048083327874295</userid>< Name>
Muy S<//Name>
< Time>
1398929446561<//Time>
< Rate>
5< /Rate>
<Text>This restaurant is a must if you are in the area for lunch, as they only serve the tsukemen ramen for lunch.

Get the tsukemen ramen with char siu pork! (I think it was $14. worth it!)

It comes with two bowls:
- one bowl with thick cold noodles, seaweed, lime, and thick slices of pork
- one bowl of thick broth with chunks of pork and the hidden treasure boiled egg ;)

I first took a sip of the broth.  It was very salty o_o
BUT... once you squeeze some lime on the noodles, dip some noodles in the broth then pull them out, it is so delicious :O !!!!

Despite what it looks like, it is a heavy meal.  The noodles are soooo good!  They have the right thickness so that when they are coated with the rich broth, the balance of salt and acidity with the lime is perfect.  The lime adds some freshness to the meal.

The pork slices are thick, and you really feel like you're getting a lot of meat with your meal.  My friend ordered extra char siu because he thought it would not be enough... but it was definitely enough meat without the extra plate.  Plus there's chunks of meat in the broth already!

Last but not least... beautiful egg.  I love you, egg.

PS: Line gets long.  Park in the residential streets.. or valet is available too.<//Text><pictures>None< /pictures><Response>None< /Response>< gmap_id>

< date>
1414185233694</date>
<username>Victor J Garza<//username>< Review>
I recently went to Tsujita for the first time as per a friends recommendation. The main feature of this place, as the name suggests is its noodles. As my friend informes me, they are now serve noodles every evening, which apparently they weren't before. What I had was the Tsukemen style ramen which is noodles on the side and ramen broth on a separate bowl for dipping the noodles into. The noodles are served cold and the broth hot. Because the noodles are cold, the broth eventually cools down. Unlike hot cooked noodles served in the magma hot broth, these noodles aren't crazy hot, so they are generally great in any weather, where's the magma hot ramen is more desirable during cold days, though not that hot weather stops me from eating any kind of ramen.
Over all, the noodles were good, the broth was thick and rich. I will definitely Tsujita again. Waits can be long, so be prepared.< /Review>

<userid>117670738005223003306</userid><username>Lily Yip<//username><Date>1408426709401< /Date><Rating>5</Rating><Review>The Best Place to get Tsukemen in LA! I promise! :)

After my trip to Japan, I've realized that this is as close as you can get to authentic tsukemen. If you never had it before, you're in for a treat. Tsukemen is basically just dipping noodles. You get a bowl of thick noodles where you dip into a bowl of thick pork broth. So good!

They even have a step-by-step menu that describes how to properly eat your tsukemen.

Order the Char Siu Tsukemen ($13.95) and you will not be disappointed. You get 5 big pieces of char siu. The portions are pretty big and I can never finish a bowl.

I love coming here on the weekdays because the wait is shorter than the crazy long lines you see on the weekends.

FYI, you can only order it during lunch-time. And it's cash only.<//Review>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>
